<dl id="n36208h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36208h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36208h"> 208(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Big-Man-Up-in-the-Sky / stuff <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36208h"><li>FW 543.29f </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36208h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36208h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36208h">MS BL 47484b-459</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:206 <a name="rBd14y" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36208h">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Atheism.]</font> <font color="green">[Charles]</font> Smith and Hopgood form the team that put Atheism across. Smith is the silent power of the movement, and Hopgood is the orator. <font color="green">[Hopgood]</font> calls the Bible a cesspool of Asiatic superstition, says that in three hundred years there won&apos;t be a church in America, and is hell-bent to rid the land of <mark>the Big-Man-up-in-the-Sky stuff</mark>. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 430</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
